<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06175010 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06175010 </ACCESS><CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: 'The American people are tired of watching hoodlums walk, ofseeing criminals mock our justice system with endless technicalities. Theywant to bring order to streets shaken by chaos and crime. '-- President Bush  </CAPTION><DESCRIPT>  US; PRESIDENT; SUPPORT; CONGRESS; ELECTION  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  President Bush used a Saturday radio address to chide Congress for stalling onhis domestic policy proposals, and challenged lawmakers to enact legislation,especially his crime and transportation packages, before its August recess.;   Bush also said Americans should reduce their dependence on government bybuilding on increased national &quot;optimism and determination&quot; as a result of thePersian Gulf war to take more personal responsibility to improve society.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Front  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  BUSH CALLS ON CONGRESS TO ACT ON DOMESTICBILLS BEFORE RECESS  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     &quot;Let's stop seeking excuses and find opportunities to serve, to help oneanother, to become sources of wealth and points of light,&quot; said Bush, drawingon a 1988 presidential campaign theme.;    &quot;For the past quarter-century,politicians in Washington have acted as if the federal government could solveevery problem, from chigger bites to earthquakes,&quot; Bush said. &quot;We all realizethat government has real limits.&quot;;    He invoked the words of John F. Kennedy,saying the Democratic president was right to tell Americans: &quot;Ask not whatyour country can do for you. Ask what you can do for your country.&quot;;   &quot;Dollars don't make visions. Deeds do,&quot; Bush said.;    Also asking lawmakers'support for the administration's initiatives on civil rights, education,public housing and banking, Bush said, &quot;There's plenty of time between now andCongress's August recess to get the job done.&quot;;    Bush criticized Congressfor failing to enact his crime package, which calls for expanded use of thedeath penalty and tightens other law enforcement mechanisms.;    &quot;The Americanpeople are tired of watching hoodlums walk, of seeing criminals mock ourjustice system with endless technicalities,&quot; Bush said. &quot;They want to bringorder to streets shaken by chaos and crime.&quot;;    He also blasted congressionalefforts to amend his transportation bill, calling it a package &quot;that wouldgive states the freedom to build the highways and transit systems they want,and not just those Washington dictates.&quot;  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Associated Press  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Washington  </CITY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910623  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Sunday  </DAY><MONTH>  June  </MONTH><PG.COL>  4A  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><FEATURE>  PHOTO  </FEATURE><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  336  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Sunday June 23, 199100175010,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>